    {
      "id": "a481fe36_1683fb98",
      "file_path": "adapters/mso-ve-vnfm-adapter/src/main/java/org/onap/so/adapters/vevnfm/util/StringUsage.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 23,
      "message": "You use this class in checkGenericVnfId method as return type, and:\nisPresent = false - means that no vnf is found\nisPresent = true - means that vnf is found, but vnfInstanceId can be null. \n\nDon't you think that this is a little overcomplicated?\n\nLet's go forward, in method receiveNotification, you check genericId.isPresent, but anyway you send this genericId to dmaap, even if it is null value. I think this is wrong.\n\nThe question is, why do you consider that null value in StringUsage can be useful for you?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2789,
        "name": "Lukasz Muszkieta",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "lukasz.muszkieta@nokia.com",
        "username": "lukaszM"
      },
      "updated": "2020-04-22 09:34:46.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "db733c40_7f77a2d1",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "4b00b859_7b495d3f",
      "file_path": "adapters/mso-ve-vnfm-adapter/src/main/java/org/onap/so/adapters/vevnfm/util/StringUsage.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 23,
      "message": "This is because even when we don't find the VnfId in the AAI we still (sometimes - when the filtering is set to ALL) want to send the message to DMaaP with this extra VnfId taken from AAI set to null.\nBut maybe we should never sent the message to DMaaP, even in such a case? \nYour question is valid. I will talk about it in my team. Thank you :-)",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5336,
        "name": "Piotr Borelowski",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "p.borelowski@partner.samsung.com",
        "username": "p.borelowski"
      },
      "updated": "2020-04-22 09:58:11.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "a481fe36_1683fb98",
      "unresolved": true
    },
